title: Why Addison Rae Is Not a Good Pop Star: From a Pop Music Fan
description: As an avid pop music fan, I always share in the excitement that comes with the arrival of a new voice in the genre. Even in an overcrowded market where stan culture can be ruthlessly competitive, I am a firm believer that there should always be room for more pop stars. Pop music can cover a wide range of subject matter, from the profound to the pointless, and all of it should be welcome. After all, there is an artistry to even the most simplistic pop song. There is a reason why Carly Rae Jepsen's "Call Me Maybe" is so catchy, and that's because it is expertly constructed, produced, and delivered. Recently, however, I have discovered a limitation to my feeling that there is a place for pointless pop music. It turns out that I do need to draw the line somewhere, and that line is at Addison Rae.The 24-year-old TikTok personality currently holds 88.4 million followers on the platform. That is no easy feat. She is a master at virality and deserves her flowers there. But when it comes to her artistic ventures outside of TikTok, virality can only get you so far, or so I thought. After initially gaining popularity through dance videos, Rae capitalized on her success by venturing into podcasting, acting, a cosmetics line, and, of course, music. Following a period of a few years in which Rae essentially threw various darts all over the dartboard, music seems to be the avenue that really stuck. Rae's successful foray into pop music, as evidenced by the generally favorable reception of her debut pop album Addison, unfortunately says more about our culture's general decline in collective "top 40" taste than anything about Rae as a musician. That's because the musicianship isn't really there. The 33-minute-long rushed album includes 12 tracks, almost half of which audiences had heard before its release, and many of which feel primed for short-form TikTok content, with abridged lengths and incomplete or missing verses. Sure, this could be a strategic business move to boost popularity on the social media platform, but once again, that conscious choice indicates what Addison Rae is really after: Virality. Pop music is a means to her end, and that is an insult to hard-working pop musicians and listeners everywhere. The problem is that we are all falling for it…
author: Ben Weiss

title: Employees share over-hyped dream jobs that sound glamorous until you actually do them: 'I'm 44, a little late to start a new career... but here I am'
description: When we were kids, dreaming about our future careers was like picking from a magical world of endless possibilities. You could be a veterinarian, a movie star, a singer, an astronaut, a dolphin trainer, or whatever your little heart desired. But then, adulthood arrived alongside a grim reality check. Maybe the years of school and six-figure debt made you wake up from that dream of becoming a doctor real quick. And being a filmmaker sounded artsy and cool, until you realized the 80-hour work weeks and constant rejection weren't exactly the vibe you were hoping for.Now we're out here scheduling spreadsheet audits at 2 p.m. and updating printer toner in beige cubicles. Welcome to the land of insurance adjusters, data entry clerks, and corporate compliance specialists. How did we get here?
author: Isabella Penn

title: 'Seeing her playing like a kitten is heartwarming': Tiger who has been chained up and forced to do tricks her entire life gets rescued, takes her very first free steps, sniffs grass, scratches a tree, and even makes a friend
description: We remember, from the time that we were kids, seeing videos on the TV of big cats doing all kinds of cool tricks in circuses. We remember the audiences cheering. We remember thinking that it was amazing. And then, we grew up, and we realized what it took for cats to do stuff like that. Nowadays, it's hard for us to look at things like this, despite the fact that we know it's still going on in some places in the world. We want to look away, but we don't think that we should. It's good to remember, and more than that, it's good to celebrate the times that big cats like that get rescued. Whether it's a lion cub getting rescued and being given a chance at a new life, if it's mountain lions getting rescued and learning to enjoy life again, or if it's a tiger getting rescued, like the one that you will be meeting today, and being given a chance, for the first time in her life, to taste freedom. And like the comments under the video say: "Such a beautiful animal. And seeing her playing like a kitten is heartwarming. I hope she lives the rest of her life in comfort and peace."Your inbox deserves hissterical cat content. We deliver. Weekly. Subscribe here.

title: Chonky black cat goes viral with hissterically unphotogenic pictures, instantly becomes the new shareable reaction meme taking the internet by storm
description: Well meowdy there, feline fam. If you're new here, welcome! We're in the business of all things cat-related, and that includes memes. We're something of an expurrt in this topic, having been around when the very first cat meme took over the internet and changed the lives of hoomans furrever. Many hissterical feline funnies have been created since then, but it's not every day you get to witness the birth of a viral cat meme. A true cat meme, not some imitation copy of something that's been done before.The OG pioneers of cat memes were such stars as Grumpy Cat, Smudge, and of course, "heavy breathing cat", but this new diamond in the rough comes from the depths of Reddit - a chonky black cat that went viral for playing with a piece of long grass. title: I Get Mail, Vol. 2
description: Hey Jerry! Yo. I just wanted to say thank you for talking up Sunderfolk. My girlfriend is not into video games AT ALL, but she likes boardgames. She was willing to give Sunderfolk a shot and has fallen completely in love with it, to the point that she asks me if we can play when I get home. I love that I can share something I have always enjoyed with her now. I hope we get more games like this in the future. Thanks again.  -Erik I love Secret Door, I love Dreamhaven, and I love Sunderfolk.  I did a sponsored panel for Sunderfolk at PAX with a bunch of other cool people and I charged zero dollars.  That's how cool I think it is.  There are quite a few gamers on PC that don't really understand "Jackbox Gloomhaven," the phone as a controller for a co-op tactics feast is either alien or distasteful, like trying to play the game with a dead rat.  I wonder sometimes if it could have a different life with a PC specific UI, but that's neither here nor there - I'm glad you two are having fun with it.  If you need naming suggestions for any of the things you discover obviously we're here to help. (CW)TB

title: CodeSOD: The Firefox Fix
description: Yitzchak was going through some old web code, and found some still in-use JavaScript to handle compatibility issues with older Firefox versions. if ($.browser.mozilla && $.browser.version.slice(0, 1) == '1') { … } What a marvel. Using JQuery, they check which browser is reported- I suspect JQuery is grabbing this from the user-agent string- and then its version. And if the version has a 1 in its first digit, we apply a "fix" for "compatibility". I guess it's a good thing there will never be more than 9 versions of Firefox. I mean, what version are they on now? Surely the version number doesn't start with a "1", nor has it started with a "1" for some time, right? title: Error'd: Squaring the Circle
description: Time Lord Jason H. has lost control of his calendar. "This is from my credit card company. A major company you have definitely heard of and depending upon the size of the area you live in, they may even have a bank branch near you. I've reloaded the page and clicked the sort button multiple times to order the rows by date in both ascending and descending order. It always ends up the same. May 17th and 18th happened twice, but not in the expected order." I must say that it is more fun when we know who they are.   A job hunter with the unlikely appelation full_name suggested titling this "[submission_title]" which seems appropriate.   "The browser wars continue to fall out in HTML email," reports Ben S. "Looking at the source code of this email, it was evidently written by & for Microsoft products (including tags!), and the author likely never saw the non-Microsoft version I'm seeing where only a haphazard assortment of the links are styled. But that doesn't explain why it's AN ELEVEN POINT SCALE arranged in a GRID."   "The owl knows who you are," sagely stated Jan. "This happens when you follow someone back. I love how I didn't have to anonymize anything in the screenshot."   "Location, location, location!" crows Tim K. who is definitely not a Time Lord. "Snarky snippet: Found while cleaning up miscellaneous accounts held by a former employee. By now we all know to expect how these lists are sorted, but what kind of sadist *created* it? Longer explanation: I wasn't sure what screenshot to send with this one, it just makes less and less sense the more I look at it, and no single segment of the list contains all of the treasures it hides. "America" seems to refer to the entire western hemisphere, but from there we either drill down directly to a city, or sometimes to a US state, then a city, or sometimes just to a country. The only context that indicates we're talking about Jamaica the island rather than Jamaica, NY is the timezone listed, assuming we can even trust those. Also, that differentiator only works during DST. There are eight entries for Indiana. There are TEN entries for the Antarctic." Well. In this case, there is a perfectly good explanation. TRWTF is time zones, that's all there is to it. These are the official IANA names as recorded in the public TZDB. In other words, this list wasn't concocted by a mere sadist, oh no. This list was cooked up by an entire committee! If you have the courage, you can learn more than you ever wanted to know about time at the IANA time zones website   [Advertisement] Keep the plebs out of prod.
